<p>When building any project, itâ€™s always a good idea to start with a simple program to make sure you have everything installed and set up correctly.  Most people call this program the â€œHello world!â€ program since the goal is to print â€œHello world!â€ to the terminal.  If you can do this, then you know everything is set up correctly and you can start building your project.</p>

<p>Before we do anything we need a directory for our project.  I put my project directories on the Desktop so we are going to do the same in this course.  Create a directory (folder) on your Desktop and call it â€œeBayScraperâ€.</p>

<p>Now open your text editor (Sublime Text 3) and select File &gt; New File.  Go to File &gt; Save As and save our new file in our â€œeBayScraperâ€ directory.  Name this file â€œscraper.rbâ€ and press save.</p>

<p>We are using the â€œ.rbâ€ file extension since our file is a Ruby file.  The â€œscraper.rbâ€ file will hold our web scraper code.  Right now though, we are going to have it print â€œHello world!â€ to our terminal.  Add the following line to â€œscraper.rbâ€.</p>

<div class="language-ruby highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="c1"># scraper.rb</span>
<span class="nb">puts</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">"Hello world!"</span><span class="p">)</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>The â€œputsâ€ function is a Ruby function that prints text to the terminal.  This is equivalent to calling â€œconsole.log()â€ in Javascript.</p>

<p>Just like Javascript, in Ruby, we call functions with parenthesis and pass arguments separated by commas in those parenthesis.  Having said that, in Ruby the parenthesis are optional.  For this course, we are going to use them so itâ€™s easier to understand what the code is doing.  When looking at other peopleâ€™s code though, itâ€™s important to know parenthesis are optional.  The above code could also be written like the following.</p>

<div class="language-ruby highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="c1"># Ruby Example</span>
<span class="nb">puts</span> <span class="s2">"Hello world!"</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>Notice how in both code snippets above, we didnâ€™t add a semicolon to the end of each line of code.  In Ruby, we donâ€™t need to add semicolons at the end of each line.</p>

<p>Save this program and letâ€™s run it.  The first thing we need to do is open our terminal (PowerShell on Windows) and navigate to our project directory.  Type the following command into your terminal and press enter to execute it.</p>

<div class="language-bash highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="c"># Terminal</span>
<span class="nb">cd</span> ~/Desktop/eBayScraper
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>Now that we are in our project directory, we can run the â€œscraper.rbâ€ file with the â€œrubyâ€ command.  Letâ€™s do that now.</p>

<div class="language-bash highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="c"># Terminal</span>
ruby scraper.rb
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>To run Ruby files, you type â€œrubyâ€ followed by the name of the file we want to run.  In our case, itâ€™s â€œscraper.rbâ€.</p>

<p>If everything worked out correctly, you should see â€œHello world!â€ printed to your terminal.</p>

